<subSubSection pageId="76" pageNumber="77" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="76.[151,1436,325,1031]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,313,845,871]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Remarks</emphasis>
. The phylogenetic analysis reveals the distinctiveness of this single specimen, and this is emphasised by the form of its treatment here. 
<bibRefCitation author="Fu, X. H. &amp; Ballantyne, L. A." box="[687,986,885,911]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" pagination="1 - 44" refId="ref104435" refString="Fu, X. H. &amp; Ballantyne, L. A. (2008) Taxonomy and behaviour of lucioline fireflies (Coleoptera: Lampyridae: Luciolinae) with redefinition and new species of Pygoluciola Wittmer from mainland China and review of Luciola LaPorte. Zootaxa 1733, 1 - 44." type="journal article" year="2008">Fu and Ballantyne (2008)</bibRefCitation>
included this species in a key to 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Luciolinae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="76" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Luciolinae</taxonomicName>
genera and figured some aspects of the aedeagus and sheath. The distinctive features of the aedeagus (especially the shape of the ML apex) suggest reproductive strategies different to those explored here in the Discussion.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
